The paper deals with interference in geometric graphs, which is a topic related to information theory and communication systems, hence the likely category of cs.IT. The use of random point sets and probability analysis suggests the category of cs.NA (numerical analysis). The study of connected graphs and minimum spanning trees points towards the category of cs.DM (discrete mathematics). The analysis of interference in graphs also relates to the category of cs.DS (data structures and algorithms). Finally, the study of interference in random point sets may also be relevant to the category of cs.SI (social and information networks).
